{{Calculus}}
A '''fluent''' is a time-varying quantity or [[variable (mathematics)|variable]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Newton|first1=Sir Isaac|title=The Method of Fluxions and Infinite Series: With Its Application to the Geometry of Curve-lines|date=1736|publisher=Henry Woodfall; and sold by John Nourse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WyQOAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=6 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> The term was used by [[Isaac Newton]] in his early [[calculus]] to describe his form of a [[function (mathematics)|function]].<ref>{{Britannica|fluxion}}</ref> The concept was introduced by Newton in 1665 and detailed in his [[mathematics|mathematical]] treatise, ''[[Method of Fluxions]]''.<ref>{{MathWorld|Fluent}}</ref> Newton described any variable that changed its value as a fluent – for example, the velocity of a ball thrown in the air. The derivative of a fluent is known as a [[fluxion]], the main focus of Newton's calculus. A fluent can be found from its corresponding fluxion through [[integral|integration]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Isaac Newton (1642-1727)|url=http://www.mhhe.com/math/calc/smithminton2e/cd/tools/timeline/newton.html|website=www.mhhe.com|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref>

