In [[mathematics]], a '''Novikov–Shubin invariant'''. introduced by {{harvs|txt|last1=Novikov|first1=Sergei|author1-link=Sergei Novikov (mathematician)|last2=Shubin|first2=Mikhail|author2-link=Mikhail Shubin (mathematician)| year=1986}},  is an invariant of a compact [[Riemannian manifold]] related to the [[spectrum (functional analysis)|spectrum]] of the [[Laplace operator]] acting on square-integrable [[differential form]]s on its universal cover. It gives a measure of the density of eigenvalues around zero. It can be computed from a triangulation of the manifold, and it is an homotopy invariant. In particular it does not depend on the chosen Riemannian metric on the manifold{{sfn|Lück|2002|p=104, Theorem 2.67}}. 

